  m_Script: {fileID: 11500000, guid: b492ab769d202ee4183275be4bff9429, type: 3}
  m_Name: A Ballad Of John Silver
  m_EditorClassIdentifier: Assembly-CSharp::FlightPaper.ProjectSorrow.Poems.PoemScriptableObject
  id: 1
  title: A Ballad Of John Silver
  author: John Masefield
  stanzas:
  - lines:
    - We were schooner-rigged and rakish, with a long and lissome hull,
    - And we flew the pretty colours of the cross-bones and the skull;
    - We'd a big black Jolly Roger flapping grimly at the fore,
    - And we sailed the Spanish Water in the happy days of yore.
  - lines:
    - We'd a long brass gun amidships, like a well-conducted ship,
    - We had each a brace of pistols and a cutlass at the hip;
    - It's a point which tells against us, and a fact to be deplored,
    - But we chased the goodly merchant-men and laid their ships aboard.
  - lines:
    - Then the dead men fouled the scuppers and the wounded filled the chains,
    - And the paint-work all was spatter-dashed with other people's brains,
    - She was boarded, she was looted, she was scuttled till she sank,
    - And the pale survivors left us by the medium of the plank.
  - lines:
    - O! then it was (while standing by the taffrail on the poop)
    - We could hear the drowning folk lament the absent chicken-coop;
    - Then, having washed the blood away, we'd little else to do
    - Than to dance a quiet hornpipe as the old salts taught us to.
  - lines:
    - O! the fiddle on the fo'c's'le, and the slapping naked soles,
    - And the genial "Down the middle, Jake, and curtsey when she rolls!"
    - With the silver seas around us and the pale moon overhead,
    - And the look-out not a-looking and his pipe-bowl glowing red.
  - lines:
    - Ah! the pig-tailed, quidding pirates and the pretty pranks we played,
    - All have since been put a stop-to by the naughty Board of Trade;
    - The schooners and the merry crews are laid away to rest,
    - A little south the sunset in the Islands of the Blest.
  rating: 3
